'''Tom<U+00E1><U+0161> Rosick<U+00FD>''' ({{IPA-cs|<U+02C8>toma<U+02D0><U+0283> <U+02C8>ros<U+026A>t<U+0361>ski<U+02D0>}}; born 4 October 1980) is a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]]. He started his professional career at his hometown club [[AC Sparta Prague]], playing three seasons in the Czech [[Gambrinus Liga]] before moving to [[Borussia Dortmund]] in 2001 for [[Deutsche Mark|DM]] 25 million (approximately [[Pound sterling|<U+00A3>]]18 million), at the time a record transfer fee paid by a [[Bundesliga]] club. He joined Arsenal in 2006.

Internationally, Rosick<U+00FD> made his debut for the Czech Republic in 2000 and became [[captain (association football)|captain]] of his country in 2006. He has taken part in three [[UEFA European Championship]]s as well as the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. He was nicknamed "the little Mozart"<ref name="G "/> for his ability to orchestrate the midfield.

== Club career ==

=== Sparta Prague ===
Rosick<U+00FD> began his career at [[AC Sparta Prague]], following his father [[Ji<U+0159><U+00ED> Rosick<U+00FD> (footballer born 1948)|Ji<U+0159><U+00ED>]] who played for the club in the 1970s and brother, [[Ji<U+0159><U+00ED> Rosick<U+00FD> (footballer born 1977)|also called Ji<U+0159><U+00ED>]] who played as a trainee in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/dec/16/newsstory.chelsea1|title=Tomas in no doubt|date=16 December 2007|accessdate=21 August 2013|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=74108.html |title=Sparta complete Rosick<U+00FD> deal |publisher=UEFA |date=10 June 2003 | accessdate = 23 June 2014}}</ref> Having played for Sparta's youth teams,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/a-league/antonis-following-rosicky-road-to-success-20111026-1mk54.html|title=Antonis following Rosicky road to success|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=27 October 2011|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> Tom<U+00E1><U+0161> debuted for Sparta's senior team in 1998 and played three matches in the 1998<U+2013>99 season,<ref name=czstats>{{cite web|url=http://www.gambrinusliga.cz/hrac/943-tom-rosick.html|title=Tom<U+00E1><U+0161> Rosick<U+00FD>|language=Czech|work=Gambrinus liga|accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> winning the [[Gambrinus Liga|national title]] with Sparta.<ref name=jerabek>{{cite book |last=Je<U+0159><U+00E1>bek|first=Lubo<U+0161>|title=<U+010C>esk<U+00FD> a <U+010D>eskoslovensk<U+00FD> fotbal <U+2013> lexikon osobnost<U+00ED> a klub<U+016F>|year=2007|publisher=Grada Publishing|location=Prague|language=Czech|isbn=978-80-247-1656-5|page=173}}</ref> He scored five goals in the [[1999<U+2013>2000 Gambrinus liga|1999<U+2013>2000]] season as the team won the league for the second year in succession.<ref name=czstats/><ref name=jerabek/> He was named the "Talent of the Year" at the 1999 [[Czech Footballer of the Year]] awards.<ref name=jerabek/> During the [[2000<U+2013>01 UEFA Champions League]] [[2000<U+2013>01 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]], he scored goals in matches against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], attracting the attention of [[Germany|German]] [[Bundesliga]] club [[Borussia Dortmund]] who had a bid accepted for the player in January 2001.<ref name=wunderkind>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/sparta-wunderkid-to-join-germanys-borussia-dortmund|title=Sparta 'Wunderkid' to join Germany's Borussia Dortmund|date=10 January 2001|accessdate=21 August 2013|work=Radio Prague}}</ref>

=== Borussia Dortmund ===
[[File:Rosicky.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Rosick<U+00FD> with [[Borussia Dortmund]] in 2006]]
On 9 January 2001, Rosick<U+00FD> joined [[Borussia Dortmund]], signing a five-year contract.<ref name=wunderkind/> His transfer fee of [[Deutsche Mark|DM]] 25 million (approximately [[Pound sterling|<U+00A3>]]18 million), made him the most expensive player in Bundesliga history and the most expensive Czech player to be sold to a foreign team.<ref name=wunderkind/><ref name="ArsenalTransfer">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/5008544.stm | title = Arsenal secure Rosicky transfer |work=BBC Sport | date = 23 May 2006 | accessdate = 23 May 2009}}</ref> In his first full season at Borussia, Rosick<U+00FD> helped the club to win the [[2001<U+2013>02 Bundesliga|2001<U+2013>02]] [[List of German football champions|Bundesliga title]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/zivotni-uspech-shodl-se-rosicky-s-kollerem-fkd-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A020504_210101_fot_zahranici_ber|title=<U+017D>ivotn<U+00ED> <U+00FA>sp<U+011B>ch, shodl se Rosick<U+00FD> s Kollerem|language=Czech|trans_title=Life's greatest achievement, agreed Rosick<U+00FD> and Koller|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad<U+00E1> fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=4 May 2002|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref> He also took part in the [[2002 UEFA Cup Final]], which Dortmund ultimately lost 3<U+2013>2 to [[Feyenoord]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Feyenoord seal Uefa Cup win |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/uefa_cup/1973191.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=8 May 2002 |accessdate=24 May 2014}}</ref> During his first two and a half seasons with the club, Rosick<U+00FD> played 75 league matches, scoring nine goals and registering 20 [[assist (football)|assists]].<ref name=03extension>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=79270.html|title=Rosick<U+00FD> extends Dortmund stay|work=UEFA|date=5 July 2003|accessdate=24 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524160301/http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=79270.html|archivedate=24 May 2014}}</ref> He subsequently agreed to extend his contract with Dortmund in July 2003, signing a deal to stay at the club until 2008.<ref name=03extension/> At the end of the season, Rosick<U+00FD> was announced as the winner of the Czech Republic's [[Golden Ball (Czech Republic)|Golden Ball]] award.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/zlaty-mic-ziskal-zaloznik-rosicky-d5b-/fot_reprez.aspx?c=A020531_204213_fot_reprez_hdv|title=Zlat<U+00FD> m<U+00ED><U+010D> z<U+00ED>skal z<U+00E1>lo<U+017E>n<U+00ED>k Rosick<U+00FD>|language=Czech|trans_title=Midfielder Rosick<U+00FD> awarded Golden Ball|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad<U+00E1> fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=31 May 2002|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref>

Although Rosick<U+00FD> was part of the Dortmund team which reached the final of the [[2003 DFB-Ligapokal]], losing 4<U+2013>2 to [[Hamburger SV|Hamburg]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/hamburk-v-ligovem-poharu-vyhral-nad-dortmundem-fr0-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A030728_225353_fot_zahranici_jam|title=Hamburk v Ligov<U+00E9>m poh<U+00E1>ru vyhr<U+00E1>l nad Dortmundem|language=Czech|trans_title=Hamburg beat Dortmund in the League Cup|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad<U+00E1> fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=28 July 2003|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref> he later described the [[2003<U+2013>04 Borussia Dortmund season|2003<U+2013>04 season]] as his "worst club season", as Dortmund failed to qualify for the following season's Champions League competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2004/06/11/rosicky-puts-euro-campaign-first|title=Rosicky puts Euro campaign first|work=The World Game|date=11 June 2004|accessdate=24 May 2014}}</ref> He scored his first competitive goal of the 2005<U+2013>06 season in February 2006, against [[MSV Duisburg]]; it was his 16th Bundesliga goal on his 139th league appearance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/konecne-jsem-dal-gol-ulevil-si-rosicky-dxo-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A060208_155628_fot_zahranici_min|title=Kone<U+010D>n<U+011B> jsem dal g<U+00F3>l, ulevil si Rosick<U+00FD>|language=Czech|trans_title=Finally I scored, sighed Rosick<U+00FD>|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad<U+00E1> fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=8 February 2006|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> March 2006 saw him have injury problems with his thigh,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/rosicky-se-po-zraneni-pomalu-chysta-do-hry-fjk-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A060317_111958_fot_zahranici_min|title=Rosick<U+00FD> se po zran<U+011B>n<U+00ED> pomalu chyst<U+00E1> do hry|language=Czech|trans_title=Rosick<U+00FD> slowly returns to play after injury|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad<U+00E1> fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=17 March 2006|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> but he scored twice in Dortmund's 4<U+2013>2 win against Hamburg at the end the month.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/rosicky-dvakrat-skoroval-za-dortmund-d8n-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A060325_195219_fot_zahranici_mn|title=Rosick<U+00FD> dvakr<U+00E1>t sk<U+00F3>roval za Dortmund|language=Czech|trans_title=Rosick<U+00FD> scored twice for Dortmund|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad<U+00E1> fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=25 March 2006|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> He was linked with a move to Spanish side [[Atl<U+00E9>tico Madrid]], which he discussed in sports magazine ''[[Kicker (sports magazine)|Kicker]]'', although mentioned in March 2006 that he hadn't signed a contract to move elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/rosicky-o-prestupu-nic-jsem-jeste-nepodepsal-fn6-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A060330_152855_fot_zahranici_min|title=Rosick<U+00FD> o p<U+0159>estupu: Nic jsem je<U+0161>t<U+011B> nepodepsal|language=Czech|trans_title=Rosick<U+00FD> on transfer: I haven't signed anything yet|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad<U+00E1> fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=30 March 2006|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>

=== Arsenal ===

==== 2006<U+2013>07 season ====
On 23 May 2006, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] confirmed that they had signed then 25-year-old Rosick<U+00FD> on a long-term contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref name="ArsenalTransfer"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/czech-midfielder-rosicky-signs-for-arsenal | title = Czech midfielder Rosicky signs for Arsenal | publisher = Arsenal.com | date = 23 May 2006 | accessdate = 23 May 2009}}</ref> He made his competitive debut for Arsenal on 8 August 2006 in a 3<U+2013>0 win over [[Dinamo Zagreb]] in a [[2006<U+2013>07 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] qualifier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=204817&cc=4716 |title=Dinamo Zagreb 0<U+2013>3 Arsenal |date=8 August 2006 |work=ESPN Soccernet |accessdate=12 October 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023180612/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=204817&cc=4716|archivedate=23 October 2012}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD> scored his first Arsenal goal on 13 September 2006 against [[Hamburger SV|Hamburg]] in Arsenal's first Champions League game of the season, which Arsenal won by two goals to one.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2345744/Rosicky-rocket-sinks-10-man-Hamburg.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Rosicky rocket sinks 10-man Hamburg | first=Christopher | last=Davies | date=14 September 2006}}</ref> On 6 January 2007, he scored twice against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Anfield]] in the [[2006<U+2013>07 FA Cup|FA Cup]], in a 3<U+2013>1 victory for Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SPORT/football/01/06/england.liverpool/index.html?eref=rss_latest | work=CNN | title=Rosicky's goals topple cup holders - CNN.com | date = 6 January 2007 | accessdate = 9 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/6213931.stm|title=Liverpool 1<U+2013>3 Arsenal |publisher=BBC |date=6 January 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009 |first=Mandeep |last=Sanghera}}</ref> In February 2007, Rosick<U+00FD> was announced as the [[Czech Footballer of the Year]] for 2006, marking his third time winning the award after previous victories in 2001 and 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=soccer&id=2755813|title=Roundup-Rosicky named Czech player of the year again|publisher=ESPN|date=6 February 2007|accessdate=13 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613143538/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=soccer&id=2755813|archivedate=13 June 2014}}</ref> He scored his first [[Premier League]] goal on 11 February 2007 against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6327211.stm|title=Arsenal 2<U+2013>1 Wigan |publisher=BBC |date=11 February 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009 |first=Sam |last=Lyon}}</ref> He also scored against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 14 April 2007<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6534721.stm|title=Arsenal 2<U+2013>1 Bolton|publisher=BBC |date=14 April 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009|first=Sam|last=Lyon}}</ref> and against [[Manchester City]] on 17 April 2007.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jeremy|last=Wilson|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/apr/18/match.sport1|title=F<U+00E1>bregas helps put Arsenal on road to Europe|date=18 April 2007|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He finished his debut season at Arsenal having scored six goals in 37 appearances for the club in all competitions.

==== 2007<U+2013>08 season ====
On 29 August, he scored in a [[2007<U+2013>08 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] qualifying match against his former club Sparta, scoring what the [[BBC]] journalist Phil Harlow described as a "quality goal", shooting the ball under Sparta's goalkeeper after receiving a pass from [[Theo Walcott]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6964144.stm | title = Arsenal 3<U+2013>0 Sparta Prague (5<U+2013>0) | publisher =  [[BBC Sport]] | date = 29 August 2007 | accessdate =23 May 2009 | first = Phil | last = Harlow}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD> scored his first Premier League goal of the season against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in a 3<U+2013>1 home win.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6963718.stm|title=Arsenal 3<U+2013>1 Portsmouth |publisher=BBC|date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009|first=John|last=May}}</ref> He scored another goal from a cross provided by Walcott in a 2<U+2013>0 October 2007 league match victory against Bolton Wanderers,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7042999.stm|title=Arsenal 2<U+2013>0 Bolton|publisher=BBC |date=20 October 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009 |first=Ian |last=Hughes}}</ref> then scored Arsenal's second goal in a 2<U+2013>0 victory over Wigan Athletic the following month, after a counter-attacking move towards the end of the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7099687.stm |title=Arsenal 2<U+2013>0 Wigan |publisher=BBC |date=24 November 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009 |first=Ian |last=Hughes}}</ref> His next league goal came in December when he scored in injury time in a 2<U+2013>1 away loss at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7122808.stm |title=Middlesbrough 2<U+2013>1 Arsenal |publisher=BBC
|date=9 December 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009 |first=Mandeep |last=Sanghera}}</ref> and he finished the month with another counter-attack goal, scoring the last of Arsenal's goals in a 4<U+2013>1 away victory against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7157408.stm |title=Everton 1<U+2013>4 Arsenal |publisher=BBC |date=29 December 2007 |accessdate=2 September 2009}}</ref> His last goal of the season came in a 3<U+2013>0 away win against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 19 January, as he scored with a volley following a pass from [[Eduardo da Silva|Eduardo]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7184820.stm |title=Fulham 0<U+2013>3 Arsenal |publisher=BBC |date=19 January 2008 |accessdate=2 September 2009 |first=Ian |last=Hughes}}</ref> A [[tendon]] injury sustained in an FA Cup match against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in January 2008 resulted in him playing no more matches that season.<ref name=noeuro2008>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/news/story?id=533411&cc=5901|title=Czech Republic captain Rosicky to miss Euro 2008|work=ESPN|date=9 May 2008|accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>

==== 2009<U+2013>10 season ====
Rosick<U+00FD> did not feature for Arsenal during the [[2008<U+2013>09 Arsenal F.C. season|2008<U+2013>09]] season due to his hamstring tendon injury. He played half of a pre-season [[exhibition game|friendly match]] against [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] in July 2009,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/8158416.stm |title=Wenger feared for Rosicky future |work=BBC Sport |date= 19 July  2009 | accessdate = 13 June 2014}}</ref> but suffered an injury to his hamstring in August, delaying his competitive return to the first team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1204716/Tomas-Rosicky-injury-stuns-Arsenal-Czech-star-ruled-weeks.html |title = Tomas Rosicky injury stuns Arsenal as Czech star is ruled out for six weeks |work=Daily Mail |location=London | accessdate = 9 May 2013 | date=6 August 2009}}</ref> On 12 September 2009, he played his first match for Arsenal since January 2008, appearing as a substitute in the league match away to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref name=injreturn09>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/match_report/0,19764,11065_3149457,00.html |title = City fire out title warning |publisher=skysports.com | date=12 September 2009 | accessdate = 9 May 2013}}</ref> He provided the pass for [[Robin van Persie]] to score Arsenal's first goal in the match and scored the second goal himself as Arsenal lost 4<U+2013>2.<ref name=injreturn09/>

On 4 January 2010, Rosick<U+00FD> signed a new contract with Arsenal stating, ""It's felt like home since I arrived here four years ago and I believe we're on the verge of achieving something special together."<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/SPORT/football/01/04/football.rosicky.arsenal.contract/ | work=CNN | title=Rosicky signs new contract with Arsenal | date = 4 January 2010 | accessdate = 12 June 2014}}</ref> Manager of Arsenal, [[Ars<U+00E8>ne Wenger]] commented on the new deal with Rosick<U+00FD> saying, "I have spoken many times of Tom<U+00E1><U+0161>' class and contribution, not only on the pitch but off it as well, and I very much feel that this new contract reflects that."<ref name=2010contract>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/8440284.stm |title=Tomas Rosicky signs new deal at Arsenal |work=BBC Sport |date= 4 January 2010 | accessdate = 9 May 2013}}</ref> Following his contract announcement, Rosick<U+00FD> scored an injury time equaliser in a 2<U+2013>2 draw at [[The Emirates Stadium]] against Everton.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8441973.stm |title=Arsenal 2 <U+2013> 2 Everton |work=BBC Sport |date= 9 January 2010 | accessdate = 27 September 2013 |first=Ian |last=Hughes}}</ref> His third goal of the season came against Bolton Wanderers, Rosick<U+00FD> scoring Arsenal's first goal at the end of the first half after Bolton had taken an early two-goal lead.<ref name=boltonjan10>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/7029573/Arsenal-4-Bolton-Wanderers-2-match-report.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Arsenal 4 Bolton Wanderers 2: match report | first=Jeremy | last=Wilson | date=20 January 2010 | accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> Arsenal went on to score three goals in the second half, winning the match 4<U+2013>2.<ref name=boltonjan10/> On 10 February 2010, Rosick<U+00FD> provided a cross for team mate [[Abou Diaby]], who resultantly scored the solitary goal of their league match against Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/174681/report |title = Diaby resuscitates title hopes |publisher=skysports.com | accessdate = 9 May 2013 |date=10 February 2010}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD> finished the season with a total of three goals in 33 appearances in all club competitions.

==== 2010<U+2013>11 season ====
[[File:Stephen Carr and Tomas Rosicky.jpg|thumb|alt=Alt text|Rosick<U+00FD> (right) playing in the Premier League against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]]]
On 15 August 2010, in the first Premier League match of the [[2010<U+2013>11 Premier League|2010<U+2013>11 season]], Rosick<U+00FD> was brought on as a substitute when Arsenal were trailing by a goal to Liverpool at Anfield, producing a cross in the 89th minute, which was diverted by [[Marouane Chamakh]] against the post. The ball then hit Liverpool goalkeeper [[Jos<U+00E9> Manuel Reina|Pepe Reina]] before crossing the line for the equalising goal as the game finished 1<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1303360/Liverpool-1-Arsenal-1-Reds-old-spirit-Joe-Coles-card-anguish.html |location=London |work=Daily Mail | title=Liverpool 1 Arsenal 1: Roy relights the Kop fire: Reds find their old spirit after Joe Cole's card anguish | first=Matt | last=Lawton | date = 17 August 2010 | accessdate = 9 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/8909559.stm |work=BBC News | title=Liverpool 1<U+2013>1 Arsenal | date=15 August 2010 | accessdate = 9 May 2013 | first = Mandeep | last = Sanghera}}</ref> He scored his only goal of the season in an FA Cup tie away to League One side [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] at [[Brisbane Road]] on 20 February 2011, with a 53rd minute header, although the match finished in a 1<U+2013>1 draw.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/9401140.stm |work=BBC Sport | title=Leyton Orient   1 - 1   Arsenal | date=20 February 2011 | accessdate = 12 June 2014 | first = Chris | last = Bevan}}</ref> On 27 February 2011, Rosick<U+00FD> started the [[2011 Football League Cup Final]] against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], playing the full 90 minutes as Arsenal were defeated 2<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/9405702.stm |work=BBC Sport | title=Arsenal   1 - 2   Birmingham | date=27 February 2011 | accessdate = 10 June 2014 | first = Philip | last = McNulty}}</ref> At the end of the campaign, Rosick<U+00FD> had scored one goal and made 34 appearances in all competitions for the Gunners.

==== 2011<U+2013>12 season ====
On 16 October 2011, Rosick<U+00FD> took part in a league game against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and was involved in the build-up play leading to Robin van Persie scoring the game's first goal after just 28 seconds, a game which finished 2<U+2013>1 to Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/249835/report |title = Actions speak louder than words |publisher=skysports.com | date=16 October 2011 | accessdate = 13 June 2014}}</ref> His first goal of the 2011<U+2013>12 season was in late February 2012 against Tottenham Hotspur. After Tottenham had taken a two-goal lead, Arsenal scored five times, with Rosick<U+00FD> scoring Arsenal's third, as they won 5<U+2013>2.<ref name=derby12>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17093405|title=Arsenal   5 - 2   Tottenham|work=BBC Sport|date=26 February 2012|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> In early March, Rosick<U+00FD> scored his team's second goal in a 3<U+2013>0 Champions League home win against [[A.C. Milan]], putting in a performance which was described by manager Ars<U+00E8>ne Wenger as "outstanding".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/football/renaissance-man-tomas-rosicky-epitomises-arsenals-revival-7543698.html | title = Renaissance man Tomas Rosicky epitomises Arsenal<U+2019>s revival | publisher = This Is London | date = 7 March 2012 | accessdate =7 March 2012 | first = James | last = Olley | location=London}}</ref> Despite the win, the club were eliminated from the competition [[Two-legged tie|on aggregate]], having been defeated 4<U+2013>0 in the previous match.<ref>{{cite news|first=Chris|last=Bevan|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17187875|title=Arsenal   3 - 0   AC Milan (agg 3 - 4)|work=BBC Sport|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>

Having been linked with a move to German side [[VfL Wolfsburg|Wolfsburg]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2011/11/25/tomas-rosicky-to-consider-arsenal-future-amid-wolfsburg-interest-233468/|title=Tomas Rosicky <U+2018>to consider Arsenal future amid Wolfsburg interest<U+2019>|work=Metro News|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD> signed a new contract with Arsenal on 12 March 2012, extending his stay at the club for another two years.<ref name=2012contract>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17340418|title=Tomas Rosicky signs new Arsenal contract|work=BBC Sport|date=12 March 2012|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD>'s performance during Arsenal's next game, a 2<U+2013>1 victory against Newcastle United, was described by Michael Da Silva of the BBC as "another impressive game" for the midfielder, although noted that he had been "guilty of a glaring miss halfway through the second half".<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Da Silva|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17254808|title=Arsenal   2 - 1   Newcastle|work=BBC Sport|date=12 March 2012|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> He sustained an injury in Arsenal's final match of the season, pulling a muscle in the game with [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/18253669|title=Euro 2012: Injured midfielder Tomas Rosicky in Czech squad|work=BBC Sport|date=29 May 2012|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>

==== 2012<U+2013>13 season ====
After picking up a serious injury to his [[achilles tendon]] at [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2178067/Tomas-Rosicky-ruled-Arsenal-season-opener.html |title=More injury woe for Arsenal as Rosicky ruled out following achilles surgery |publisher=Daily Mail |date=24 July 2012 | accessdate = 9 May 2013}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD> made his first club appearance of the 2012<U+2013>13 season in Arsenal's 2<U+2013>0 home defeat against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on 1 December 2012.<ref name=soccerbaseprofile>{{cite web|title=Tomas Rosicky|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=17885|work=Soccerbase|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> He played in the Champions League three days later, scoring Arsenal's only goal in a 2<U+2013>1 loss against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] in Greece.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2013/matches/round=2000347/match=2009579/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Arsenal miss top spot with defeat at Olympiacos |publisher=UEFA |date=4 December 2012 | accessdate = 9 May 2013}}</ref> In April 2013 he scored both of Arsenal's goals in their 2<U+2013>1 away victory against West Bromwich Albion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21979771 |title=West Brom 1<U+2013>2 Arsenal |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |work=[[BBC]] |date=6 April 2013|accessdate=13 April 2013|last=Ornstein|first=David}}</ref> He managed 16 competitive appearances for Arsenal, scoring three times in the 2012<U+2013>13 season.

==== 2013<U+2013>14 season ====
On 4 January 2014, Rosick<U+00FD> scored his first goal of the season in a 2<U+2013>0 win in the FA Cup against Tottenham Hotspur, winning the ball on the halfway line from [[Danny Rose (footballer, born 1990)|Danny Rose]] before running to the goal and beating opposition goalkeeper [[Hugo Lloris]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Taylor|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jan/04/arsenal-tottenham-hotspur-fa-cup-match-report|title=Tomas Rosicky seals Arsenal's cruise past Tottenham Hotspur in FA Cup|date=4 January 2014|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref>
During the 2<U+2013>1 victory against Aston Villa just over a week later, his nose was broken in two places after a challenge by [[Gabriel Agbonlahor]], requiring surgery after the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/arsenal-v-fulham-tomas-rosicky-could-feature-despite-broken-nose-as-arsene-wenger-welcomes-back-fitagain-aaron-ramsey-9067846.html|title=Arsenal v Fulham: Tomas Rosicky could feature despite broken nose as Arsene Wenger welcomes back fit-again Aaron Ramsey|publisher=The Independent|date=17 January 2014|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> February saw Rosick<U+00FD> score "one of the best [goals] we have scored", according to Wenger, in a 4<U+2013>1 league victory against Sunderland. <ref name=sunderland-feb14>{{cite news|first=David|last=Hytner|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/23/tomas-rosicky-arsenal-sunderland-arsene-wenger|title=Tomas Rosicky scores in Arsenal win over Sunderland and agrees new deal|date=23 February 2014|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref>

In March 2014, Rosick<U+00FD> signed a contract extension with ''the Gunners'', keeping him at the club for an additional two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/per-mertesacker-and-tomas-rosicky-sign-arsenal-contracts--but-future-of-bacary-sagna-thrown-into-doubt-9168323.html|title=Per Mertesacker and Tomas Rosicky sign Arsenal contracts - but future of Bacary Sagna thrown into doubt|publisher=The Independent|date=4 March 2014|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> Later the same month, Rosick<U+00FD> scored Arsenal's winning goal in a 1<U+2013>0 [[North London Derby]] victory for Arsenal, against Tottenham, at [[White Hart Lane]]. <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26502628 | title = BBC Sport - Tottenham Hotspur 0-1 Arsenal | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 16 March 2014 | accessdate = 16 March 2014}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD> concluded the season by winning his first trophy in English football, coming on as an extra time substitute in the [[2014 FA Cup Final]] as Arsenal beat [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] 3<U+2013>2 at Wembley Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27354148| title=Arsenal 3-2 Hull|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/20140517/rosicky-it-was-exhausting-to-watch | title = Rosicky - It was exhausting to watch | publisher = arsenal.com | date = 17 May 2014 | accessdate = 13 June 2014}}</ref>

== International career ==
Rosick<U+00FD> made his international debut for the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] in February 2000 at the age of 19 against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref name=rsssf-intgoals>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/rosicky-intl.html |title=Tomas Rosicky - Goals in International Matches |publisher= Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=10 April 2014 |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> He played two more friendly matches before being named in the Czech Republic's provisional 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]].<ref name=rsssf-intgoals/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/may/22/newsstory.sport5|title=Euro 2000 provisional squads|date=22 May 2000|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He played in his nation's first two matches at Euro 2000 during [[Patrik Berger]]'s international [[suspension (punishment)|suspension]] <U+2013> both losses <U+2013> before Berger replaced him ahead of the Czech Republic's final game, against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/800887.stm | title = Smicer brace gives Czechs win | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 21 June 2000 | accessdate = 13 June 2014}}</ref>

He took part in [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualification for the 2002 World Cup]], scoring twice in a 6<U+2013>0 win against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]].<ref name=bel2001>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/2002/world_cup/countdown/news/2001/11/13/czech_belgium/|title=Rosicky to lead weakened Czechs against Belgium|work=CNN Sports Illustrated|date=13 November 2001|accessdate=24 May 2014}}</ref> After finishing second in their qualifying group, the Czech Republic played a two-legged playoff against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]]. Rosick<U+00FD> was unable to take part in the first game, a 1<U+2013>0 loss, due to suspension;<ref name=bel2001/> in the second match he played in the 1<U+2013>0 loss as Belgium qualified for the 2002 World Cup at the Czechs' expense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=4395/preliminaries/preliminary=3835/matches/match=24856/report.html|title=Match Report Czech Republic <U+2013> Belgium|work=FIFA|date=14 November 2001|accessdate=|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130630225155/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=4395/preliminaries/preliminary=3835/matches/match=24856/report.html|archivedate=30 June 2013}}</ref>

He played at [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] and helped the side qualify for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] in Germany. Rosick<U+00FD> scored seven times in 12 matches during the qualifying process.<ref name=rsssf-intgoals/> The last of these was the only goal of the second leg of the Czech Republic's play-off against [[Norway national football team|Norway]], ensuring qualification for the finals.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4435458.stm | title = Czech Republic 1<U+2013>0 Norway | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 16 November 2005 | accessdate = 27 September 2013}}</ref>

At the 2006 World Cup finals, Rosick<U+00FD> scored two goals in the Czech Republic's opening match on 12 June 2006 in a 3<U+2013>0 victory over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], the first of which was from {{convert|30|yd|m}} out.<ref name=usa06>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852720.stm|title=USA 0-3 Czech Republic|work=BBC Sport|date=12 June 2006|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> He was named as the FIFA [[Man of the Match]] for his performance.<ref name=usa06/> Rosick<U+00FD> played the whole 90 minutes of his country's subsequent matches, against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] and [[Italy national football team|Italy]], but the Czech Republic lost both games by a 2<U+2013>0 scoreline and progressed no further in the tournament.<ref name=ghana06>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853102.stm|title=Czech Republic 0-2 Ghana|work=BBC Sport|date=17 June 2006|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=italy06>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853358.stm|title=Czech Republic 0-2 Italy|work=BBC Sport|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref>

In August 2006, Rosick<U+00FD> was made [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of the Czech Republic national side, replacing the retiring [[Pavel Nedv<U+011B>d]] in advance of the [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying]] process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SPORT/football/08/30/czech.rosicky/index.html?section=cnn_latest|title=Czechs name Rosicky as new captain|work=CNN|date=30 August 2006|accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> His last appearance of the qualifying campaign was against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] in November 2007.<ref name=sm09>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/6163683/Arsenals-Tomas-Rosicky-plays-first-match-in-20-months.html|title=Arsenal's Tomas Rosicky plays first match in 20 months|work=The Telegraph|date=9 September 2009|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> Rosick<U+00FD> missed [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] due to injury, announcing his absence in May 2008.<ref name=noeuro2008/> He returned to international football when he started for the Czech Republic on 9 September 2009, in a World Cup qualifier against [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]], following a 20 month absence due to injury.<ref name=sm09/> The game finished 7<U+2013>0 to the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=760185.html |title=Baro<U+0161> hits four as Czechs stay alive |publisher=UEFA |date=9 September 2009 | accessdate = 23 June 2014}}</ref>

Rosick<U+00FD> captained the Czech Republic in their opening two matches at [[UEFA Euro 2012]].  However, an [[achilles tendon]] injury in the second match, a 2<U+2013>1 win over [[Greece national football team|Greece]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2012/jun/12/euro-2012-greece-czech-republic-group-a | title = Euro 2012: Czechs suffer Tomas Rosicky setback after win over Greece | publisher = The Guardian | date = 12 June 2012 | accessdate = 9 May 2013 | first = Sid | last = Lowe}}</ref> ended Rosick<U+00FD>'s tournament, as the Czechs were eliminated in the quarter-finals by [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18355069 | title = Czech Rep. 0<U+2013>1 Portugal | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 21 June 2012 | accessdate = 9 May 2013 | first = Tom | last = Rostance}}</ref>

== Style of play ==
Ahead of his first senior international tournament, Rosick<U+00FD> was described by the BBC as "a solid playmaker".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/czech_rep/squad/774803.stm | title = Tomas Rosicky | publisher = BBC Sport | date = | accessdate = 13 June 2014}}</ref> Arsenal manager Wenger described Rosick<U+00FD> as having "great technique, skill on the ball and sharp passing".<ref name="ArsenalTransfer"/> Upon signing a contract extension in 2010, Wenger called him a "special talent" and said his "vision and touch is remarkable".<ref name=2010contract/> Announcing Rosick<U+00FD>'s 2012 contract extension, Wenger called him "technically top class".<ref name=2012contract/>

Rosick<U+00FD> is also well known for preferring to use his outside of the foot for passing and shooting.<ref>http://footballonlineworld.com/biographies/tomas-rosicky-biography/</ref> In Germany, he gained the nickname "The Little Mozart" for his ability to orchestrate play on the pitch.<ref name="G">{{cite news | url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2007/aug/15/newsstory.championsleague1 | title=Little Mozart goes home intending to upset his first love | work=The Guardian | date=15 August 2007 | accessdate=23 May 2009 | last=Hytner | first=David | location=London}}</ref> David Hytner of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described him as "the all-round midfielder who brings balance, organisation and urgency to the team".<ref name=sunderland-feb14/>

